Sep 17 2009 	Location location location!	After reading the hundreds of reviews of this hotel and finding that the vast majority was very positive, almost unanimously, we booked 10 nights there. Although the photos do not lie, I had the impression that it was a large hotel on the crescent. However, it is only one of several hotels lined almost one after the other in the same crescent. All small hotels, with only one entrance door and few rooms. From the photo of the twin room we did not expect that we would not have enough room to open two suitcases, so be forewarned, the rooms are very small. The door between the beds in the photo is the door to the bathroom, however, it has only the toilet and a box shower. The sink is in the room. So, when they say insuite, that is what they mean. The shower stall is so small that anyone over 166 pounds and taller than 5'11' would have trouble soaping himself or herself. The breakfast is included and maybe if you are there for just a couple of days it would be ok. However, one gets tired of two pieces of toast, beans (from a can, Heinz beans), one egg and bacon or sausage (which I did not eat, as I don't eat pork), plus juice and cold cereals get tiring after a couple of days. There is no fruit or yogurt. Of course, there is no elevator, which could be a problem for some people, having to carry suitcases up a narrow set of stairs for 2 or 3 floors. There is one terminal for internet, but it was not always working, although, if you have your own computer we would be able to use it there. The main positive point of this hotel, and I assume any of the other ones in the same crescent, is the location: 5 minutes on foot from the underground Russel station (Picadilly line directly from Heathrow airport to the station; no need to change, and in that station the access to the street is by elevator), 5 minutes from Euston station and train station, 5 minutes from Kings Cross/St. Pancras station and train station. Lots of restaurants around, 5 minutes from the British Museum and the British Library and 20 minutes on foot to Soho. The other positive point is that it is in a quiet area. Yes, you can hear the odd step of the guest above you, but you don't hear traffic or street noise, except occasionally in the week end when people leave the pubs.I guess it is value for money and I would recommend it for those who want what it is considered an inexpensive centrally located hotel in London. Would I go back? Maybe, but I would do even more research and see if I could find other options before booking there again.For Canadians, like us, for the equivalent of 95 pounds per night, we would have gotten a lot more here or in the U.S and in many other countries. So, my advice is to check the other hotels in the same crescent, Cartwright Gardens, and see whether and how it compares with the Euro.	
