May 15 2009 	Top value at good location	In a city where the cost of a decent hotel easily eats well beyond your original travel budget, the Euro is a very welcome exception. The rooms are big enough for you to store your luggage, and still be able to move about. The bathrooms are also quite spacious, and in very nice condition – even though you'll have to do with the rather pointless British two-tap system, with one tap for cold water and another for warm. The beds are rather neutral, and will not cause any problems. In addition the room provides a closet, TV, radiator and coffee/ tea.Also, as a clear positive, Breakfast is included in your stay, and you can choose a full English or from a variation of cereals. One of the few negatives worth mentioning are the single layer windows, which are a bit drafty.The nearby King's Cross area is bustling with travellers, workers and traffic, but take two steps aside to the Cartwright Gardens and the Euro Hotel, and you'll feel you're miles away. The Euro is just one of a crescent of hotels occupying a charming row of buildings, which are all located just behind a small park with tennis courts. You'll wake up to the song of birds rather than the noise of heavy traffic.King's Cross and St Pancras stations are still not more than a few minutes walk away. From there you have direct connection to both Heathrow and Gatwick airports, as well as the Northern, Victoria, Piccadilly, Hammersmith &amp; City, Circle and Metropolitan tube lines for easy connection with all of London. If the big King's Cross St Pancras gets to crowdy or complex, the Euro is also within a few minutes walk from both Euston (Northern and Victoria) and Russel Square (Piccadilly) tube stations.The area's without any big sights and great shopping opportunities, but being such a busy area there are lots of choices for eating, drinking and buying your everyday needs. (e.g. Pizza Express, just round the corner on Euston Road). If you should feel the need for something more without travelling to far, there's a small shopping centre (Brunswick) near Russel Square, and some good restaurant options past King's Cross up towards Islington.The Euro isn't fancy or luxurious, but if you're looking for a good value hotel with a good location it should be a safe bet.	
