Sep 1 2008 	Walked Everywhere	After an overnight flight from Minnesota we boarded the Picadilly Line Underground at Heathrow for what felt like a long ride to Russell Square Station, but once we arrived and settled in we were struck by what an ideal location this is for exploring London. To stretch our legs after the flight we headed out exploring to the south. In an amazingly short time we were on a bridge over the Thames, looking at Big Ben and the houses of Parliament in the distance. If you like to walk, you can walk from the Euro Hotel to many parts of London.In a pleasant surprise our reserved basement room became a 2nd (U.S. 3rd) floor sunny space with a large double bed and two twin beds, still for the basic rate for two persons. For a four night stay, it was nice for each of us to have a bed to lay our suitcase out on.The location was very quiet, we slept well with the windows open to the street. The only sounds during the night were an occasional boisterous guest returning to one of the many pleasant looking hotels on this crescent.Breakfast, as advertised, was cooked fresh to order with a choice of eggs, sausage, bacon, beans, tomatoes, and “white or brown” toast. Coffee, juice, and cereals were available also. We found that most days we could eat a hearty breakfast and simply pick up a snack during the day.In the evening there are three great eating spots within a block, the North Sea Fish, the Tandoori Indian, and a “gastro pub” with extensive tapas in addition to vegetarian and British dishes… all down Leigh Street.We took the tube back from Waterloo Station after a play at the Young Vic, and tubed over to Green Park to visit Churchill’s wartime bunker, but most of the time we found it very doable to walk everywhere. Definitely a convenient, friendly, and well-run base for a visit to London.	
